Nominators are asked to consider the nominee‚Äôs instructional methods, community involvement, embodiment of the Teays Valley Guiding Principles, ability to make a difference, dedication to the teaching profession and rapport with students, parents and peers.

post_text: We are excited to welcome Kahn to Viking Nation!
shared_text:
Pickaway County Sheriff's Office
June 19 at 12:26 PM ¬∑

Sheriff Robert Radcliff is pleased to announce that Deputy Pete Bowers and his K-9 Partner Kahn have completed training and are ready for duty.

Deputy Bowers, who is a school resource officer in the Teays Valley District will have Kahn available for any situation that arises. Although stationed at Teays Valley Schools, Kahn and Deputy Bowers will be available for any school in the county.

Along with K-9 Michael Blue, that is trained in explosives detection, the county schools have the availability of two K-9's for use.

Kahn is a 2 1/2 year old Belgian Malinois that is trained in narcotic detection.

We want to welcome Kahn and congratulate Deputy Bowers on their successful training!

shared_text:
Scioto Post was live.
April 9 at 1:01 PM ¬∑

Carmen Tarbill a teacher at Ashville Elementary challenges her gifted students to a Vikes Project.

Student Arjuim Sreekanth was originally researching a Vikes project that involved how people enjoyed classic cars and bringing them to a car show. Sadly because of COVID-19 those plans were dashed and Arjun needed to find another way to complete his project, thats when he came up with the Classic car driving parade. He was originally going to a car show with the Roundtown Cruisers in Circleville Ohio.

This was his alternate decision bringing joy to the manors in Pickaway County.

post_text: The students in one TV neighborhood have found a way to have some fun while working on their skills. TVHS German teacher Lindsay Spradlin wrote some positive messages in German with sidewalk chalk on the common walking paths around the neighborhood. German students have been responding to them and even writing more questions and answers to each other. Spanish students have started getting in on the fun too. Mrs. Spradlin is encouraging World Language students all over the district to pick up some chalk and go out and write too!

post_text: Attention parents! Information about the remote learning plan now that the school closure has been extended until May 1 can be found at this link - https://bit.ly/2xPYDhY. It is a lengthy document, but our hope is that it answers all of the most common questions. As you read through it, we hope you see that our biggest emphasis and concern is for the well-being of our students. While we want our students to continue to enhance their education while we are away from school, we understand this is an unprecedented time where families are dealing with hardships and unique situations. If you have any questions, please email your teachers.

post_text: As most of you have probably heard, Governor DeWine announced today that he has extended the school closure until May 1. Please have your students continue to work on the learning opportunities that are being provided to them this week. If you have any questions about them, contact the teachers via email.
